{"title_page": "Tramontana (sports car)", "text_new": "{{advert|date=August 2018}}<br />{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Tramontana\n| image = 2009 Tramontana R.jpg\n| manufacturer = Atelier Tramontana\n| production = 2007-present\n| assembly = [[Barcelona]], [[Spain]]<br />[[Andorra la Vella]], [[Andorra]]\n| designer = \n| class = [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])\n| body_style = 2-seater [[Formula One]]-inspired\n| layout = [[Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel drive layout]]\n| engine = '''V10 Version:'''<br />{{convert|5.2|L|cuin|abbr=on|0}} [[V10 engine|V10]] [[naturally aspirated]] {{convert|660|PS|kW bhp|0|lk=on|abbr=on}}<br /> '''V12 Version:'''<br />{{convert|5.5|L|cuin|abbr=on|0}} [[V12 engine|V12]] twin-[[turbocharged]] {{convert|900|PS|kW bhp|0|lk=on|abbr=on}}\n| transmission = 6-speed [[Semi-automatic transmission|sequential]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|3050|mm|in|1}}\n| length = {{convert|4900|mm|in|1}}\n| width = {{convert|2080|mm|in|1}}\n| height = {{convert|1220-1275|mm|in|1}}\n| weight = {{convert|1268|kg|lb|0}}\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| homepage = {{URL|www.tramontanacorp.com}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Tramontana Car''' is a [[mid-engine design|mid-engine]]d [[Spain|Spanish]] [[sports car]] with styling inspired by combining [[Formula One]] racing cars and [[jet-fighters]]. Tramontana is a pure driver's supercar for authentic engine lovers. It is built by [[Atelier Tramontana]], in [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]] ([[Spain]]). It was launched as a [[Concept car|concept]] at the 2005 [[Geneva Motor Show]], and subsequently modified for production. It began as a project with the aim of breaking with conventionalisms and creating a new family of [[supercar]]s. Only 6 a year are manufactured and they are all made under special request. In 2009, Tramontana introduced a closed top model named Tramontana R.,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.km77.com/00/tramontana/r/2009/t01.asp|title=Km77.com article|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.evo.co.uk/carreviews/evocarreviews/235370/tramontana_r_edition.html|title=EVO Magazine article}}</ref> and the XTR version in 2012.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autobild.es/noticias/tramontana-xtr-186646|title=Tramontana XTR, m\u00e1s potencia para el deportivo espa\u00f1ol|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://noticias.coches.com/noticias-motor/tramontana-xtr-el-superdeportivo-espanol-sube-a-888-cv/56383|title=Tramontana XTR, el superdeportivo espa\u00f1ol sube a 888 CV}}</ref> The company is focused on the '''Tramontana Car''', which is a [[bespoke]] [[supercar]] fully customizable by the driver.\n\n==Overview==\n\nEach unit requires over 4000 working hours. '''Tramontana''' clients are meticulously chosen. There are no two identical units; once a '''Tramontana''' is produced, there will be no other like it. The vehicle took over ten years of development to get to its current state, an arduous undertaking from the engineering team and the active Formula 1 drivers who took part in the process.\n\n===Engine and Transmission===\nThe most radical models are the Tramontana GT and the Tramontana XTR. The car is fitted with an aluminium [[mid-engined]] 5.500cc [[double overhead cam]] [[V12 engine|V12]] [[Mercedes-Benz]], twin-turbocharged engine that produces up to {{convert|900|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} and 980Nm (678lbs of torque). Each [[Mercedes-Benz]] engine is rebuilt, modified and reassembled by Tramontana's racing engineers. Before fitting it into the car, Atelier Tramontana carries out a rigorous test of each engine at their production plant in Barcelona. '''Tramontana''' opted from its beginnings to drastically limit its annual production in order to maintain exhaustive control over each unit produced.\n\nOther models are fitted with a V10 naturally aspirated engine that develops {{convert|660|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}.  This, in combination with a 6-speed sequential gearbox, launches the car from 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h in under 2.8 seconds,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automoblog.net/2009/02/26/tramontana-r-edition-a-carbon-fiber-v12-monster/|title=Tramontana R Edition - A Carbon Fiber V12 Monster|publisher=Automoblog.net}}</ref> and it gets a top speed of more than {{convert|325|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}.\n\n===Exterior and Interior===\n[[Atelier Tramontana]] established that each car has to be different from every other unit produced by the company. They define their product as a [[bespoke]] [[supercar]] where every detail is designed by and for the driver. As with a Formula 1, there are only a few units.\n\nThe Tramontana is made up of the [[carbon fibre]] [[monocoque]] [[chassis]], with a honeycomb-shaped structure that provides minimal density and extremely high resistance. The [[Formula One]] safety cell that cocoons the driver, protecting them from injuries, allows weight reduction for the car. The Tramontana's carbon fiber monocoque was defined under FIA design and security standards. The chassis rigidity is synonymous with high performance, chiefly in the world of high competition, since it is one of the key factors in the dynamics of the vehicle, in addition to the suspension system. The Tramontana chassis is the most rigid in the world, even more than that of an authentic Formula 1. It supports 40G's of force before deforming.\n \nEach curve in the bodywork was meticulously calculated and optimized to generate more than 250&nbsp;kg of [[downforce]], and lateral cornering forces of 1.3 [[g-force|G]] at high speeds. The Tramontana is fully customizable by the client, but the standard package comes with forged aluminum wheels, measuring 20\". Highlights include different aerodynamic options available to be chosen depending on the use of the car, and a single [[canopy door]] that allows access to the [[tandem]] [[cockpit]]. This helps the mass distribution of the vehicle. If the two seat option is chosen, the passenger sits directly behind and slightly higher than the driver, resembling a [[fighter-jet]]s [[tandem]] position. \n\nThe interior is a mix of [[aluminium]], [[carbon fibre]] and [[leather]]. The customer also has the option to decorate the interior with gold and other fine materials. Only one of each car interior is produced and cannot be replicated. The [[Hood (vehicle)|bonnet]] badge is made of solid [[white gold]].\n\n=== Vehicle dynamics ===\nThe car weighs {{convert|1268|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}, with a suitable weight distribution and a low center of gravity, which allows it to\u00a0turn curves at higher speeds.\n\nTramontana equips the car with elements of the highest possible performance. The suspension is an adjustable \u00d6hlins [[double wishbone suspension|double wishbone]], a sequential six-speed paddle shift transmission, 380mm carbon-ceramic disc brakes with 6-piston AP Racing caliper. \n\nThe car has a suspension lifting system to adjust ride height depending on the road conditions. Electronic aids like traction control system and ABS are adjustable for different driving modes, from 0 (manual control) to 6.\n\n=== History ===\n\nThe Tramontana was launched as a [[Concept car|concept]] at the 2005 [[Geneva Motor Show]], and was subsequently modified for production. In 2009, Tramontana introduced a closed top model named Tramontana R.,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> and the XTR version in 2012.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nFrom the beginning, this automaker maintains a policy of super-confidentiality and extreme rigor in the sales process while choosing the end customer.\n\nThis inaccessibility of the automaker towards the average customer, even though it has sufficient resources to acquire the vehicle, has resulted in the brand obtaining recognition among collectors. At present there are units in Europe, America, the Arab Emirates and China, but there is no information about their final customers or their exact location. One unit was spotted on an episode of [[Live PD]] during a traffic stop in East Providence, RI, USA on 8/23/2019. <ref>Live PD Rewind, Episode #258, aired 8/23/2019, A&E Network</ref>\n\nThe first vehicle built was the Concept Car fitted with a V10 engine.\n\nTramontana built an exclusive series of eight  Tramontana cars, the GT and XTR. Car No.1 in the series was the factory test vehicle, which was used to perform dynamic improvements of the vehicle. Nowadays it is almost certainly the most improved unit. Cars No.2 and No.3 were sold in Beijing. Car No.4 of was acquired in Abu Dhabi, and car No.5 in Germany. The next two units were destined for the North American market. The last unit, No.8 out of 8, is currently in Spain, at the company's family headquarters. There is no exact record of the price, but the price is set between \u20ac800,000 ($911,000) and \u20ac1,100,000 ($1,253,000)\n\nIn 2019, the company continues developing its models and researching modern technology, chiefly regarding alternative propulsion technologies.\n\nThey have also worked on a 100% electric Tramontana intended for drift competitions.\n\n== Models ==\n[[Tramontana C-Edition|C-Edition]] (V10 600 hp & V12 550 hp)\n\n[[Tramontana S-Edition|S-Edition]] (V10 600 hp & V12 550 hp)\n\n[[Tramontana R-Edition|R-Edition]] (V10 600 hp & V12 550-720 hp)\n\n[[Tramontana XTR|XTR]] (V12 720/888 hp)\n\n== Specifications ==\n\n=== Engines ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Type\n!Layout\n!Displacement\n!Admission\n!Max Power\n!Specific Output\n!Max Torque\n!Compression\n!Fuel\n|-\n|5.2 litre V10 - 90\u00ba, FSI\n|Mid-engine, Longitudinal Alignment Rear Wheel Drive\n|5.204 cm<sup>3</sup> / 317,6 in<sup>3</sup>\n|Naturally Aspirated\n|600 hp / 447kW / at 8.500 rpm\n|115 hp-litre / 86kW-litre / 2,13 hp in<sup>3</sup> / 1,58kW in<sup>3</sup>\n|580 Nm / 428lbs / ft. from 6.500 rpm\n|12,5:1\n|Unleaded 98 octanes\n|-\n|5.5 litre V12 - 60\u00ba, SFI Biturbo\n|Mid-engine, Longitudinal Alignment Rear Wheel Drive\n|5.513 cm<sup>3</sup> / 336,4 in<sup>3</sup> \n|Twin Turbochargers\n|888 hp / 653 kW / at 5.850 rpm\n|130 hp-litre / 96kW-litre / 1,88 hp in<sup>3</sup> / 1,41kW in<sup>3</sup>\n|920 Nm / 678lbs / ft. from 4.000 rpm\n|9:1\n|Unleaded 98 octanes\n|}\n\n==In video games==\nThe Tramontana appears as a playable vehicle in ''[[Asphalt 8: Airborne]]'' and ''[[Asphalt (series)|Asphalt Nitro]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://tramontanacorp.com/ Official Tramontana web site]\n\n{{Automotive industry in Spain}}\n\n[[Category:Cars of Spain]]\n[[Category:Car manufacturers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:Flagship vehicles]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Catalonia]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established in 2005]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=August 2018}}<br />{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Tramontana\n| image = 2009 Tramontana R.jpg\n| manufacturer = Atelier Tramontana\n| production = 2007-present\n| assembly = [[Barcelona]], [[Spain]]<br />[[Andorra la Vella]], [[Andorra]]\n| designer = \n| class = [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])\n| body_style = 2-seater [[Formula One]]-inspired\n| layout = [[Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel drive layout]]\n| engine = '''V10 Version:'''<br />{{convert|5.2|L|cuin|abbr=on|0}} [[V10 engine|V10]] [[naturally aspirated]] {{convert|660|PS|kW bhp|0|lk=on|abbr=on}}<br /> '''V12 Version:'''<br />{{convert|5.5|L|cuin|abbr=on|0}} [[V12 engine|V12]] twin-[[turbocharged]] {{convert|900|PS|kW bhp|0|lk=on|abbr=on}}\n| transmission = 6-speed [[Semi-automatic transmission|sequential]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|3050|mm|in|1}}\n| length = {{convert|4900|mm|in|1}}\n| width = {{convert|2080|mm|in|1}}\n| height = {{convert|1220-1275|mm|in|1}}\n| weight = {{convert|1268|kg|lb|0}}\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| homepage = {{URL|www.tramontanacorp.com}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Tramontana Car''' is a [[mid-engine design|mid-engine]]d [[Spain|Spanish]] [[sports car]] with styling inspired by combining [[Formula One]] racing cars and [[jet-fighters]]. Tramontana is a pure driver's supercar for authentic engine lovers. It is built by [[Atelier Tramontana]], in [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]] ([[Spain]]). It was launched as a [[Concept car|concept]] at the 2005 [[Geneva Motor Show]], and subsequently modified for production. It began as a project with the aim of breaking with conventionalisms and creating a new family of [[supercar]]s. Only 6 a year are manufactured and they are all made under special request. In 2009, Tramontana introduced a closed top model named Tramontana R.,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.km77.com/00/tramontana/r/2009/t01.asp|title=Km77.com article|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.evo.co.uk/carreviews/evocarreviews/235370/tramontana_r_edition.html|title=EVO Magazine article}}</ref> and the XTR version in 2012.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autobild.es/noticias/tramontana-xtr-186646|title=Tramontana XTR, m\u00e1s potencia para el deportivo espa\u00f1ol|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://noticias.coches.com/noticias-motor/tramontana-xtr-el-superdeportivo-espanol-sube-a-888-cv/56383|title=Tramontana XTR, el superdeportivo espa\u00f1ol sube a 888 CV}}</ref> The company is focused on the '''Tramontana Car''', which is a [[bespoke]] [[supercar]] fully customizable by the driver.\n\n==Overview==\n\nEach unit requires over 4000 working hours. '''Tramontana''' clients are meticulously chosen. There are no two identical units; once a '''Tramontana''' is produced, there will be no other like it. The vehicle took over ten years of development to get to its current state, an arduous undertaking from the engineering team and the active Formula 1 drivers who took part in the process.\n\n===Engine and Transmission===\nThe most radical models are the Tramontana GT and the Tramontana XTR. The car is fitted with an aluminium [[mid-engined]] 5.500cc [[double overhead cam]] [[V12 engine|V12]] [[Mercedes-Benz]], twin-turbocharged engine that produces up to {{convert|900|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} and 980Nm (678lbs of torque). Each [[Mercedes-Benz]] engine is rebuilt, modified and reassembled by Tramontana's racing engineers. Before fitting it into the car, Atelier Tramontana carries out a rigorous test of each engine at their production plant in Barcelona. '''Tramontana''' opted from its beginnings to drastically limit its annual production in order to maintain exhaustive control over each unit produced.\n\nOther models are fitted with a V10 naturally aspirated engine that develops {{convert|660|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}.  This, in combination with a 6-speed sequential gearbox, launches the car from 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h in under 2.8 seconds,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automoblog.net/2009/02/26/tramontana-r-edition-a-carbon-fiber-v12-monster/|title=Tramontana R Edition - A Carbon Fiber V12 Monster|publisher=Automoblog.net}}</ref> and it gets a top speed of more than {{convert|325|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}.\n\n===Exterior and Interior===\n[[Atelier Tramontana]] established that each car has to be different from every other unit produced by the company. They define their product as a [[bespoke]] [[supercar]] where every detail is designed by and for the driver. As with a Formula 1, there are only a few units.\n\nThe Tramontana is made up of the [[carbon fibre]] [[monocoque]] [[chassis]], with a honeycomb-shaped structure that provides minimal density and extremely high resistance. The [[Formula One]] safety cell that cocoons the driver, protecting them from injuries, allows weight reduction for the car. The Tramontana's carbon fiber monocoque was defined under FIA design and security standards. The chassis rigidity is synonymous with high performance, chiefly in the world of high competition, since it is one of the key factors in the dynamics of the vehicle, in addition to the suspension system. The Tramontana chassis is the most rigid in the world, even more than that of an authentic Formula 1. It supports 40G's of force before deforming.\n \nEach curve in the bodywork was meticulously calculated and optimized to generate more than 250&nbsp;kg of [[downforce]], and lateral cornering forces of 1.3 [[g-force|G]] at high speeds. The Tramontana is fully customizable by the client, but the standard package comes with forged aluminum wheels, measuring 20\". Highlights include different aerodynamic options available to be chosen depending on the use of the car, and a single [[canopy door]] that allows access to the [[tandem]] [[cockpit]]. This helps the mass distribution of the vehicle. If the two seat option is chosen, the passenger sits directly behind and slightly higher than the driver, resembling a [[fighter-jet]]s [[tandem]] position. \n\nThe interior is a mix of [[aluminium]], [[carbon fibre]] and [[leather]]. The customer also has the option to decorate the interior with gold and other fine materials. Only one of each car interior is produced and cannot be replicated. The [[Hood (vehicle)|bonnet]] badge is made of solid [[white gold]].\n\n=== Vehicle dynamics ===\nThe car weighs {{convert|1268|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}, with a suitable weight distribution and a low center of gravity, which allows it to\u00a0turn curves at higher speeds.\n\nTramontana equips the car with elements of the highest possible performance. The suspension is an adjustable \u00d6hlins [[double wishbone suspension|double wishbone]], a sequential six-speed paddle shift transmission, 380mm carbon-ceramic disc brakes with 6-piston AP Racing caliper. \n\nThe car has a suspension lifting system to adjust ride height depending on the road conditions. Electronic aids like traction control system and ABS are adjustable for different driving modes, from 0 (manual control) to 6.\n\n=== History ===\n\nThe Tramontana was launched as a [[Concept car|concept]] at the 2005 [[Geneva Motor Show]], and was subsequently modified for production. In 2009, Tramontana introduced a closed top model named Tramontana R.,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> and the XTR version in 2012.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nFrom the beginning, this automaker maintains a policy of super-confidentiality and extreme rigor in the sales process while choosing the end customer.\n\nThis inaccessibility of the automaker towards the average customer, even though it has sufficient resources to acquire the vehicle, has resulted in the brand obtaining recognition among collectors. At present there are units in Europe, America, the Arab Emirates and China, but there is no information about their final customers or their exact location. One unit was spotted on an episode of [[Live PD]] during a traffic stop in East Providence, RI, USA on 8/23/2019. <ref>Live PD Rewind, Episode #258, aired 8/23/2019, A&E Network</ref>\n\nThe first vehicle built was the Concept Car fitted with a V10 engine.\n\nTramontana built an exclusive series of eight  Tramontana cars, the GT and XTR. Car No.1 in the series was the factory test vehicle, which was used to perform dynamic improvements of the vehicle. Nowadays it is almost certainly the most improved unit. Cars No.2 and No.3 were sold in Beijing. Car No.4 of was acquired in Abu Dhabi, and car No.5 in Germany. The next two units were destined for the North American market. The last unit, No.8 out of 8, is currently in Spain, at the company's family headquarters. There is no exact record of the price, but the price is set between \u20ac800,000 ($911,000) and \u20ac1,100,000 ($1,253,000)\n\nIn 2019, the company continues developing its models and researching modern technology, chiefly regarding alternative propulsion technologies.\n\nThey have also worked on a 100% electric Tramontana intended for drift competitions.\n\n==In video games==\nThe Tramontana appears as a playable vehicle in ''[[Asphalt 8: Airborne]]'' and ''[[Asphalt (series)|Asphalt Nitro]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://tramontanacorp.com/ Official Tramontana web site]\n\n{{Automotive industry in Spain}}\n\n[[Category:Cars of Spain]]\n[[Category:Car manufacturers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:2000s cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:Flagship vehicles]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Catalonia]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established in 2005]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish brands]]\n", "name_user": "Untazal", "label": "safe", "comment": "Complete list of models built and current engine types with their full specs. Based on the info available on the official Tramontana website (http://tramontanacorp.com/details)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tramontana_(sports_car)"}
