 = [[Tripura Tribal Areas Autonomous District Council|Chief Executive Member]]\n| constituency4  = \n| term_start4    = 2005\n| term_end4      = 2008\n| predecessor4   = \n| successor4     = Ranjit Debbarma\n| office5        = [[Tripura Tribal Areas Autonomous District Council|Chief Executive Member]]\n| constituency5  = \n| term_start5    = 1985\n| term_end5      = 1991\n| predecessor5   = \n| successor5     = \n| party          = [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)|CPI(M)]] \n| religion       = \n| spouse         = Smt. Malati Deb Barma \n| college        = \n| children       = \n| alma_mater     = \n| faculty        = \n| website        =  \n| source         = \n}}\n\n'''Aghore Debbarma''' is an Indian politician and a former Agriculture minister of the [[Tripura]] state.<ref name=\"BT\"/>\n\nAs a member of the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] (CPI-M), he represented Ashrambari [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency of [[Khowai district]]. He served as a minister of Tripura for Agriculture, Tribal Welfare, Animal resources. He is also a central committee member of CPI-M and Leader of GMP, the tribal wing of CPI-M.<ref>{{cite news |title=Full list: CPI(M) newly elected central committee and politburo members |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/full-list-cpim-newly-elected-central-committee-and-politburo-members-sitaram-yechury-5147330/ |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=The Indian Express |publisher=The Indian Express |date=22 April 2018}}</ref> In 2018, he lost the [[2018 Tripura Legislative Assembly election|Legislative Assembly election]] to [[Mewar Kumar Jamatia|Mevar Kumar Jamatiya]] of [[Indigenous People's Front of Tripura]] (IPFT).<ref name=\"BT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/tripura-agriculture-minister-loses-118030300332_1.html |title=Tripura agriculture minister loses |newspaper=Business Standard |date=3 March 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Desk |first1=India com News |title=Tripura Agriculture Minister Aghore Debbarma Loses {{!}} \u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092a\u0941\u0930\u093e \u0915\u0947 \u0915\u0943\u0937\u093f \u092e\u0902\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0905\u0918\u094b\u0930\u0947 \u0926\u0947\u092c\u092c\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e \u091a\u0941\u0928\u093e\u0935 \u0939\u093e\u0930\u0947 |url=https://www.india.com/hindi-news/india-hindi/tripura-agriculture-minister-aghore-debbarma-loses-2924197/ |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=India News, Breaking News, Entertainment News {{!}} India.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Politcal career ==\nDuring 1985 Debbarma was elected as Chief Executive Member of [[Tripura Tribal Areas Autonomous District Council]]. He was again elected as  Chief Executive Member of [[Tripura Tribal Areas Autonomous District Council]] in 2005.<ref name=\"TA\"/> He was also a Cabinet minister of Tribal Welfare,Agriculture & Animal Resource Development from 2008 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=TRIPURAINFOWAY : Tripura's Latest News, Views & IT Portal |url=http://www.tripurainfoway.com/news-details/TN/53905/agriculture-minister-aghore-debbarma-inaugurates-fresher-rsquo-s-training-program-on-bee-keeping.html |website=www.tripurainfoway.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Organic farming: Tripura to take lessons from Sikkim |url=https://www.thestatesman.com/cities/organic-farming-tripura-to-take-lessons-from-sikkim-1488009338.html |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=The Statesman |agency=IANS |date=25 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Award ==\nHe was awarded Krishi Karman Award 2015-16 by [[Government of India]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tripura gets national award for record food production |url=https://www.thestatesman.com/cities/tripura-gets-national-award-for-record-food-production-1492599909.html |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=The Statesman |agency=IANS |date=19 April 2017}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award Title\n! Year\n|-\n| Krishi Karman Award\n| 2015-16\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Communist Party of India (Marxist)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Debbarma, Aghore}}\n[[Category:Tripura politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of India (Marxist) politicians]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of India (Marxist) politicians from Tripura]]\n[[Category:Tripura politicians]]\n\n{{CPIndiaMarxist-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aghore_Debbarma"}
{"title_page": "Harold Lloyd Jr.", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Harold Lloyd Jr.\n| image        = Flaming Urge.jpg\n| caption      = Harold Lloyd Jr. in ''[[The Flaming Urge]]''\n| birth_name   = Harold Clayton Lloyd Jr.\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1931|1|25}}\n| birth_place  = [[Beverly Hills, California]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1971|6|9|1931|1|25}}\n| death_place  = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| education    =\n| alma_mater   =\n| occupation   = Actor, singer\n| years_active = 1950&ndash;1965\n| other_names  =\n| parents      = [[Harold Lloyd]]<br>[[Mildred Davis]]\n| website      =\n}}\n'''Harold Clayton Lloyd Jr.''' (January 25, 1931 \u2013 June 9, 1971) was an American actor and singer.\n\n==Career==\nThe second child and only son of the silent film comedian [[Harold Lloyd]] and actress [[Mildred Davis]], Lloyd made several [[B-movies]] in the 1950s and 1960s, including ''[[The Flaming Urge]]'' (1953) (his only starring role) and ''[[Frankenstein's Daughter]]'' (1958). In 1959, he had a role in the film ''[[Girls Town]]'', which featured the son of another famous silent movie comedian, [[Charles Chaplin Jr.]] He was given production roles in the compilations of his father's films, released in the early 1960s. As a singer, he performed in several films, had moderate successes in cabaret in Hollywood and elsewhere, and released an album of romantic ballads in 1965 titled ''Intimate Style''.\n\n==Personal life==\nLloyd (known as Dukey to his family) found it very difficult to live in the shadow of his very famous father, and was an alcoholic from his 20s onward.<ref>Dardis, Tom (1983). ''[[Harold Lloyd: The Man on the Clock]]''. Viking. {{ISBN|0-14-007555-0}}.</ref> He was also gay at a time when it was considered socially unacceptable. Author Tom Dardis notes that Lloyd Sr. was understanding about his son's sexuality, all the more so given Lloyd Jr.'s tendency toward violent lovers. Consequently, the younger Lloyd often returned to [[Harold Lloyd Estate|Greenacres]], the family estate, battered and bruised after his encounters. His father's tolerance had its limits, however, and (in not an uncommon view at the time) Lloyd Sr. blamed his own absences during his son's childhood for his sexuality.<ref>Lambro, Phillip (2007) ''Close Encounters of the Worst Kind''. Lulu.com {{ISBN|978-1-4303-0401-2}}</ref> In 1953, he briefly was engaged to the Chilean actress Marina Cisternas. In 1960, he was again engaged, this time to Parisian socialite Irene Barrelet deRicou, daughter of French tennis player [[Paul Barrelet de Ricou]] and socialite Louise Barrelet de Ricou.<ref>''[[Press-Telegram|Long Beach Independent]]'' newspaper, Saturday, April 9, 1960</ref> Irene was warned by many, including [[Bing Crosby]], not to marry Lloyd, but it wasn't until she caught him with another man that the wedding was canceled. He had a home in Palm Springs, California <ref>|lccn=2008022210 |url=http://www.barricadebooks.com/index.php/books/single/a_city_comes_out/ |oclc=209646547 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617074829/http://www.barricadebooks.com/index.php/books/single/a_city_comes_out |archivedate=2013-06-17 }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nLloyd suffered a massive [[stroke]] in 1965 from which he never fully recovered. He died on June 9, 1971 at the age of 40, three months after the death of his father.  He was interred with his parents in a crypt in the Great Mausoleum's Begonia Corridor at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)|Glendale Forest Lawn Cemetery]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1950|| ''[[Our Very Own (1950 film)|Our Very Own]]'' || Student || Uncredited\n|-\n|1953|| ''[[The Flaming Urge]]'' || Tom Smith ||\n|-\n|1955|| ''[[A Yank in Ermine]]'' || Butch ||\n|-\n|1958|| ''[[Father Knows Best]]'' || Joel || Credited television appearance\n|-\n|1958|| ''[[Frankenstein's Daughter]]'' || Don ||\n|-\n|1959|| ''[[Girls Town]]'' || Chip Gardner ||\n|-\n|1960|| ''[[Platinum High School]]'' || Charlie-Boy Cable ||\n|-\n|1960|| ''[[Sex Kittens Go to College]]'' || Policeman ||\n|-\n|1962|| ''Married Too Young'' || Tommy Blaine ||\n|-\n|1965|| ''[[Mutiny in Outer Space]]'' || Sgt. Andrews || (final film role)\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|name=Harold Lloyd Jr.|id=0515907}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111006203322/http://www.radiationcinema.com/2009/04/richard-cunha-and-power-of-moment.html Review of ''Frankenstein's Daughter'']\n* [https://archive.org/details/Flaming_Urge_1953 ''The Flaming Urge'' online at The Internet Archive]\n* {{FAG|5457}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lloyd, Harold Jr.}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Palm Springs, California]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Palm Springs, California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American musicians]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Harold Lloyd Jr.\n| image        = Flaming Urge.jpg\n| caption      = Harold Lloyd Jr. in ''[[The Flaming Urge]]''\n| birth_name   = Harold Clayton Lloyd Jr.\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1931|1|25}}\n| birth_place  = [[Beverly Hills, California]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1971|6|9|1931|1|25}}\n| death_place  = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| education    =\n| alma_mater   =\n| occupation   = Actor, singer\n| years_active = 1950&ndash;1965\n| other_names  =\n| parents      = [[Harold Lloyd]]<br>[[Mildred Davis]]\n| website      =\n}}\n'''Harold Clayton Lloyd Jr.''' (January 25, 1931 \u2013 June 9, 1971) was an American actor and singer.\n\n==Career==\nThe second child and only son of the silent film comedian [[Harold Lloyd]] and actress [[Mildred Davis]], Lloyd made several [[B-movies]] in the 1950s and 1960s, including ''[[The Flaming Urge]]'' (1953) (his only starring role) and ''[[Frankenstein's Daughter]]'' (1958). In 1959, he had a role in the film ''[[Girls Town]]'', which featured the son of another famous silent movie comedian, [[Charles Chaplin Jr.]] He was given production roles in the compilations of his father's films, released in the early 1960s. As a singer, he performed in several films, had moderate successes in cabaret in Hollywood and elsewhere, and released an album of romantic ballads in 1965 titled ''Intimate Style''.\n\n==Personal life==\nLloyd (known as Dukey to his family) found it very difficult to live in the shadow of his very famous father, and was an alcoholic from his 20s onward.<ref>Dardis, Tom (1983). ''[[Harold Lloyd: The Man on the Clock]]''. Viking. {{ISBN|0-14-007555-0}}.</ref> He was also gay at a time when it was considered socially unacceptable. Author Tom Dardis notes that Lloyd Sr. was understanding about his son's sexuality, all the more so given Lloyd Jr.'s tendency toward violent lovers. Consequently, the younger Lloyd often returned to [[Harold Lloyd Estate|Greenacres]], the family estate, battered and bruised after his encounters. His father's tolerance had its limits, however, and (in not an uncommon view at the time) Lloyd Sr. blamed his own absences during his son's childhood for his sexuality.<ref>Lambro, Phillip (2007) ''Close Encounters of the Worst Kind''. Lulu.com {{ISBN|978-1-4303-0401-2}}</ref> In 1953, he briefly was engaged to the Chilean actress Marina Cisternas. In 1960, he was again engaged, this time to Parisian socialite Irene Barrelet deRicou, daughter of French tennis player [[Paul Barrelet de Ricou]] and socialite Louise Barrelet de Ricou.<ref>''[[Press-Telegram|Long Beach Independent]]'' newspaper, Saturday, April 9, 1960</ref> Irene was warned by many, including [[Bing Crosby]], not to marry Lloyd, but it wasn't until she caught him with another man that the wedding was canceled. He had a home in Palm Springs, California |lccn=2008022210 |url=http://www.barricadebooks.com/index.php/books/single/a_city_comes_out/ |oclc=209646547 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617074829/http://www.barricadebooks.com/index.php/books/single/a_city_comes_out |archivedate=2013-06-17 }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nLloyd suffered a massive [[stroke]] in 1965 from which he never fully recovered. He died on June 9, 1971 at the age of 40, three months after the death of his father.  He was interred with his parents in a crypt in the Great Mausoleum's Begonia Corridor at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)|Glendale Forest Lawn Cemetery]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1950|| ''[[Our Very Own (1950 film)|Our Very Own]]'' || Student || Uncredited\n|-\n|1953|| ''[[The Flaming Urge]]'' || Tom Smith ||\n|-\n|1955|| ''[[A Yank in Ermine]]'' || Butch ||\n|-\n|1958|| ''[[Father Knows Best]]'' || Joel || Credited television appearance\n|-\n|1958|| ''[[Frankenstein's Daughter]]'' || Don ||\n|-\n|1959|| ''[[Girls Town]]'' || Chip Gardner ||\n|-\n|1960|| ''[[Platinum High School]]'' || Charlie-Boy Cable ||\n|-\n|1960|| ''[[Sex Kittens Go to College]]'' || Policeman ||\n|-\n|1962|| ''Married Too Young'' || Tommy Blaine ||\n|-\n|1965|| ''[[Mutiny in Outer Space]]'' || Sgt. Andrews || (final film role)\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|name=Harold Lloyd Jr.|id=0515907}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20111006203322/http://www.radiationcinema.com/2009/04/richard-cunha-and-power-of-moment.html Review of ''Frankenstein's Daughter'']\n* [https://archive.org/details/Flaming_Urge_1953 ''The Flaming Urge'' online at The Internet Archive]\n* {{FAG|5457}}\