     = \n| grounds_area        = \n| architect           = \n| architecture_firm   = \n| developer           =\n| engineer            =\n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| main_contractor     = \n| awards              = \n| designations        = \n| known_for           =\n| ren_architect       = \n| ren_firm            = \n| ren_engineer        =\n| ren_str_engineer    = \n| ren_serv_engineer   = \n| ren_civ_engineer    = \n| ren_oth_designers   = \n| ren_qty_surveyor    = \n| ren_contractor      =\n| ren_awards          = \n| seating_type        = \n| seating_capacity    = \n| rooms               = \n| parking             = \n| website             = [https://www.musikverein.at/en musikverein.at]\n| embed               =\n| embedded            = \n| references          = \n| footnotes           =\n}}\nThe '''{{Lang|de|Wiener Musikverein|italic=no}}''' ({{IPA-de|\u02ccvi\u02d0n\u0250  mu\u02cczi\u02d0kf\u0259\u0281\u02c8e\u026an|at}}; Viennese Music Association), commonly shortened to {{Lang|de|Musikverein|italic=no}}, is a [[concert hall]] in the [[Innere Stadt]] borough of [[Vienna]], [[Austria]]. It is the home of the [[Vienna Philharmonic]] orchestra.\n\nThe superb acoustics of the \"Great Hall\" ({{Lang|de|Gro\u00dfer Saal}}) place it among the finest concert halls in the world, along with Berlin's [[Konzerthaus Berlin|Konzerthaus]], the [[Concertgebouw]] in Amsterdam, and Boston's [[Symphony Hall, Boston|Symphony Hall]].<ref>Long, Marshall, [https://web.archive.org/web/20120204134309/http://www.mlacoustics.com/PDF/Shoebox.pdf \"What is So Special About Shoebox Halls? Envelopment, Envelopment, Envelopment\"], ''Acoustics Today'', April 2009, pp. 21\u201325.</ref> With the exception of Boston Symphony Hall,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bso.org/brands/symphony-hall/about-us/historyarchives/the-history-of-symphony-hall.aspx|title=The History of Symphony Hall|publisher=[[Boston Symphony Orchestra]]|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"nrhpinv2\">{{Cite journal|url={{NHLS url|id=99000633}}|title=National Historic Landmark Nomination: Symphony Hall|date=June 26, 1998 |format=PDF |author1=Gerrit Petersen |author2=Steven Ledbetter |author3=Kimberly Alexander Shilland  |last-author-amp=yes |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=2020-04-12}}</ref> none of these halls were built in the modern era with the application of architectural acoustics, and all share a long, tall, and narrow [[Shoebox style|shoebox]] shape.\n\n==Building==\nThe building is located on {{ill|Dumbastra\u00dfe|de}}/{{ill|B\u00f6sendorferstra\u00dfe|de}} behind the [[Hotel Imperial]] near the [[Ringstra\u00dfe]] boulevard and the [[Wien (river)|Wien River]], between B\u00f6sendorferstra\u00dfe and [[Karlsplatz]]. However, since B\u00f6sendorferstra\u00dfe is a relatively small street, the building is better known as being between Karlsplatz and K\u00e4rntner Ring (part of Ringstra\u00dfe loop). It was erected as the new concert hall run by the {{Lang|de|[[Gesellschaft der Musikfreunde]]|italic=no}}, on a piece of land provided by Emperor [[Franz Joseph I of Austria]] in 1863. \n\nThe plans were designed by Danish architect [[Theophil Hansen]] in the [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]] style of an [[ancient Greek temple]], including a concert hall and a smaller [[chamber music]] hall. The building was inaugurated on 6 January 1870.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musikverein.at/dermusikverein/musikvereinssaal.php?lang=en|title=Gro\u00dfer Musikvereinssaal|publisher=Wiener Musikverein|language=English|accessdate=20 December 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222173724/https://www.musikverein.at/dermusikverein/musikvereinssaal.php?lang=en|archivedate=22 December 2015}}</ref> A major donor was [[Nikolaus Dumba]], industrialist and liberal politician of Greek descent, whose name the Austrian government gave to one of the streets surrounding the {{Lang|de|Musikverein|italic=no}}.\n[[File:Musikverein Goldener Saal.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Great Hall, also known as Golden Hall]]\n\nThe {{Lang|de|Gro\u00dfer Musikvereinssaal|italic=no}} (Great Hall), or {{Lang|de|Goldener Saal|italic=no}} (Golden Hall), is about {{convert|49|m|ft|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|19|m|ft|abbr=on}} wide, and {{convert|18|m|ft|abbr=on}} high. It has 1,744 seats and standing room for 300. The [[Skandalkonzert]] of 1913 was given there, and it is the venue for the annual [[Vienna New Year's Concert]]. \n\nThe Great Hall's lively acoustics are primarily based on Hansen's intuition, as he could not rely on any studies on [[architectural acoustics]]. The room's rectangular shape and proportions, its boxes and sculptures allow early and numerous sound [[Reflection (physics)|reflections]]. \n\nThe Hall originally included a historic [[pipe organ]] built by [[Friedrich Ladegast]]. Its first organ recital was held by [[Anton Bruckner]] in 1872. The present-day instrument was originally installed in 1907 by the Austrian firm of [[Rieger Orgelbau]], highly esteemed by musicians such as [[Franz Schmidt]] or [[Marcel Dupr\u00e9]], and rebuilt in 2011.\n[[File:The Wiener Musikverein (8336449001).jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|December 2012]]\nSince 2001, the building has been undergoing renovation, and several new rehearsal halls have been installed in the basement.\n\n==Halls==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Venue\n!Size\n!Height\n!Seats\n|-\n|{{Lang|de|Gro\u00dfer Musikvereinssaal|italic=no}} (Goldener Saal)\n|align=right|48.8&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;19.1&nbsp;m\n|align=right|17.75&nbsp;m\n|1744 seats and c. 300 standing\n|-\n|{{Lang|de|Brahmssaal|italic=no}}\n|align=right|32.5 \u00d7 10.3&nbsp;m\n|align=right|11 m\n|600 seats\n|-\n|{{Lang|de|Gl\u00e4serner Saal|italic=no}}/Magna Auditorium\n|align=right|22 \u00d7 12.5&nbsp;m\n|align=right|8 m\n|380 seats\n|-\n|{{Lang|de|Metallener Saal|italic=no}}\n|align=right|10.5 \u00d7 10.8&nbsp;m\n|align=right|3.2 m\n|70 seats\n|-\n|{{Lang|de|Steinerner Saal|italic=no}}/Horst Haschek Auditorium\n|align=right|13 \u00d7 ~8.6&nbsp;m\n|align=right|~3.3m\n|60 seats\n|-\n|{{Lang|de|H\u00f6lzerner Saal|italic=no}} (not used for concerts)\n|align=right|11.5 \u00d7 7.5&nbsp;m\n|align=right|3.4m\n|60 seats\n|}\nThe names of the six halls refer to gold, [[Johannes Brahms]], glass, metal, stone and wood respectively.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Musikverein, Vienna|Musikverein}}\n* {{official|https://www.musikverein.at/en}}\n\n{{Music venues in Austria}}\n{{coord|48|12|02|N|16|22|20|E|region:AT-9_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Music venues completed in 1870]]\n[[Category:Cultural venues in Vienna]]\n[[Category:Concert halls in Austria]]\n[[Category:Vienna Philharmonic]]\n[[Category:Event venues established in 1870]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Innere Stadt]]\n[[Category:Theophil Hansen buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                = Wiener Musikverein\n| native_name         =\n| native_name_lang    =\n| logo                =\n| logo_size           =\n| logo_alt            =\n| logo_caption        =\n| image               = Musikverein Vienna June 2006 480.jpg\n| image_size          =\n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = June 2006\n| map_type            = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| map_size            =\n| map_dot_label       =\n| relief              = \n| former_names        = \n| alternate_names     = \n| etymology           = \n| status              = \n| cancelled           =\n| topped_out          =\n| building_type       = [[Concert hall]]\n| architectural_style = [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]]\n| classification      =\n| location            = \n| address             = \n| location_town       = [[Vienna]]\n| location_country    = Austria\n| coordinates         = \n| altitude            =\n| current_tenants     = [[Vienna Philharmonic]]\n| namesake            =\n| groundbreaking_date = \n| start_date          =\n| topped_out_date     =\n| completion_date     = \n| opened_date         = \n| inauguration_date   = {{start date|df=y|1870|1|6}}\n| relocated_date      = \n| renovation_date     = \n| closing_date        = \n| demolition_date     = \n| cost                = \n| ren_cost            = \n| client              = \n| owner               = \n| landlord            = \n| affiliation         =\n| height              = \n| architectural       = \n| tip                 = \n| antenna_spire       = \n| roof                = \n| top_floor           = \n| observatory         = \n| diameter            = \n| circumference       = \n| weight              =\n| other_dimensions    = \n| structural_system   = \n| material            = \n| size                =\n| floor_count         = \n| floor_area          = \n| elevator_count      = \n| grounds_area        = \n| architect           = \n| architecture_firm   = \n| developer           =\n| engineer            =\n| structural_engineer = \n| services_engineer   = \n| civil_engineer      = \n| other_designers     = \n| quantity_surveyor   = \n| main_contractor     = \n| awards              = \n| designations        = \n| known_for           =\n| ren_architect       = \n| ren_firm            = \n| ren_engineer        =\n| ren_str_engineer    = \n| ren_serv_engineer   = \n| ren_civ_engineer    = \n| ren_oth_designers   = \n| ren_qty_surveyor    = \n| ren_contractor      =\n| ren_awards          = \n| seating_type        = \n| seating_capacity    = \n| rooms               = \n| parking             = \n| website             = [https://www.musikverein.at/en musikverein.at]\n| embed               =\n| embedded            = \n| references          = \n| footnotes           =\n}}\nThe '''{{Lang|de|Wiener Musikverein|italic=no}}''' ({{IPA-de|\u02ccvi\u02d0n\u0250  mu\u02cczi\u02d0kf\u0259\u0281\u02c8e\u026an|at}}; Viennese Music Association), commonly shortened to {{Lang|de|Musikverein|italic=no}}, is a [[concert hall]] in the [[Innere Stadt]] borough of [[Vienna]], [[Austria]]. It is the home of the [[Vienna Philharmonic]] orchestra.\n\nThe superb acoustics of the \"Great Hall\" ({{Lang|de|Gro\u00dfer Saal}}) place it among the finest concert halls in the world, along with Berlin's [[Konzerthaus Berlin|Konzerthaus]], the [[Concertgebouw]] in Amsterdam, and Boston's [[Symphony Hall, Boston|Symphony Hall]].<ref>Long, Marshall, [https://web.archive.org/web/20120204134309/http://www.mlacoustics.com/PDF/Shoebox.pdf \"What is So Special About Shoebox Halls? Envelopment, Envelopment, Envelopment\"], ''Acoustics Today'', April 2009, pp. 21\u201325.</ref> With the exception of Boston Symphony Hall,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bso.org/brands/symphony-hall/about-us/historyarchives/the-history-of-symphony-hall.aspx|title=The History of Symphony Hall|publisher=[[Boston Symphony Orchestra]]|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref> none of these halls were built in the modern era with the application of architectural acoustics, and all share a long, tall, and narrow [[Shoebox style|shoebox]] shape.\n\n==Building==\nThe building is located on {{ill|Dumbastra\u00dfe|de}}/{{ill|B\u00f6sendorferstra\u00dfe|de}} behind the [[Hotel Imperial]] near the [[Ringstra\u00dfe]] boulevard and the [[Wien (river)|Wien River]], between B\u00f6sendorferstra\u00dfe and [[Karlsplatz]]. However, since B\u00f6sendorferstra\u00dfe is a relatively small street, the building is better known as being between Karlsplatz and K\u00e4rntner Ring (part of Ringstra\u00dfe loop). It was erected as the new concert hall run by the {{Lang|de|[[Gesellschaft der Musikfreunde]]|italic=no}}, on a piece of land provided by Emperor [[Franz Joseph I of Austria]] in 1863. \n\nThe plans were designed by Danish architect [[Theophil Hansen]] in the [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]] style of an [[ancient Greek temple]], including a concert hall and a smaller [[chamber music]] hall. The building was inaugurated on 6 January 1870.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musikverein.at/dermusikverein/musikvereinssaal.php?lang=en|title=Gro\u00dfer Musikvereinssaal|publisher=Wiener Musikverein|language=English|accessdate=20 December 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222173724/https://www.musikverein.at/dermusikverein/musikvereinssaal.php?lang=en|archivedate=22 December 2015}}</ref> A major donor was [[Nikolaus Dumba]], industrialist and liberal politician of Greek descent, whose name the Austrian government gave to one of the streets surrounding the {{Lang|de|Musikverein|italic=no}}.\n[[File:Musikverein Goldener Saal.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Great Hall, also known as Golden Hall]]\n\nThe {{Lang|de|Gro\u00dfer Musikvereinssaal|italic=no}} (Great Hall), or {{Lang|de|Goldener Saal|italic=no}} (Golden Hall), is about {{convert|49|m|ft|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|19|m|ft|abbr=on}} wide, and {{convert|18|m|ft|abbr=on}} high. It has 1,744 seats and standing room for 300. The [[Skandalkonzert]] of 1913 was given there, and it is the venue for the annual [[Vienna New Year's Concert]]. \n\nThe Great Hall's lively acoustics are primarily based on Hansen's intuition, as he could not rely on any studies on [[architectural acoustics]]. The room's rectangular shape and proportions, its boxes and sculptures allow early and numerous sound [[Reflection (physics)|reflections]]. \n\nThe Hall originally included a historic [[pipe organ]] built by [[Friedrich Ladegast]]. Its first organ recital was held by [[Anton Bruckner]] in 1872. The present-day instrument was originally installed in 1907 by the Austrian firm of [[Rieger Orgelbau]], highly esteemed by musicians such as [[Franz Schmidt]] or [[Marcel Dupr\u00e9]], and rebuilt in 2011.\n[[File:The Wiener Musikverein (8336449001).jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|December 2012]]\nSince 2001, the building has been undergoing renovation, and several new rehearsal halls have been installed in the basement.\n\n==Halls==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Venue\n!Size\n!Height\n!Seats\n|-\n|{{Lang|de|Gro\u00dfer Musikvereinssaal|italic=no}} (Goldener Saal)\n|align=right|48.8&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;19.1&nbsp;m\n|align=right|17.75&nbsp;m\n|1744 seats and c. 300 standing\n|-\n|{{Lang|de|Brahmssaal|italic=no}}\n|align=right|32.5 \u00d7 10.3&nbsp;m\n|align=right|11 m\n|600 seats\n|-\n|{{Lang|de|Gl\u00e4serner Saal|italic=no}}/Magna Auditorium\n|align=right|22 \u00d7 12.5&nbsp;m\n|align=right|8 m\n|380 seats\n|-\n|{{Lang|de|Metallener Saal|italic=no}}\n|align=right|10.5 \u00d7 10.8&nbsp;m\n|align=right|3.2 m\n|70 seats\n|-\n|{{Lang|de|Steinerner Saal|italic=no}}/Horst Haschek Auditorium\n|align=right|13 \u00d7 ~8.6&nbsp;m\n|align=right|~3.3m\n|60 seats\n|-\n|{{Lang|de|H\u00f6lzerner Saal|italic=no}} (not used for concerts)\n|align=right|11.5 \u00d7 7.5&nbsp;m\n|align=right|3.4m\n|60 seats\n|}\nThe names of the six halls refer to gold, [[Johannes Brahms]], glass, metal, stone and wood respectively.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Musikverein, Vienna|Musikverein}}\n* {{official|https://www.musikverein.at/en}}\n\n{{Music venues in Austria}}\n{{coord|48|12|02|N|16|22|20|E|region:AT-9_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Music venues completed in 1870]]\n[[Category:Cultural venues in Vienna]]\n[[Category:Concert halls in Austria]]\n[[Category:Vienna Philharmonic]]\n[[Category:Event venues established in 1870]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Innere Stadt]]\n[[Category:Theophil Hansen buildings]]\n", "name_user": "Inventis", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Musikverein"}
{"title_page": "Barry Lando", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Barry Lando\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1939|06|8|df=y}}\n| nationality        = Canadian\n| occupation         = Journalist, Author and Producer\n| television         = CBS' 60 Minutes\n| website            = http://BarryMLando.com/\n}}\n\n'''Barry Lando''' (born June 8, 1939) is a Canadian award-winning journalist, author, and former producer for [[CBS]]' ''[[60 Minutes]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Keefe|first1=Derrick|title=Web of Deceit By Barry M. Lando|url=https://www.straight.com/article-68130/web-of-deceit-by-barry-m-lando|accessdate=8 July 2015|work=Georgia Straight|date=January 31, 2007|location=Vancouver}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nLando graduated from [[Harvard University]] in 1961<ref>{{cite news|title=Students to Start New Publication|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1962/3/10/students-to-start-new-publication-pa/|accessdate=15 July 2015|work=Harvard Crimson|date=March 10, 1962}}</ref> and [[Columbia University]].{{citation needed|date=July 2015}} He was a producer for ''[[60 Minutes]]'' for over 25 years, most of those producing stories for [[Mike Wallace]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lando|first1=Barry|title=My Quarter Century With Mike Wallace|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/barry-lando/mike-wallace-dies-60-minutes_b_1412516.html|accessdate=9 July 2015|work=Huffington Post|date=June 9, 2012}}</ref> Lando produced the first interview with the [[Ayatollah]] [[Khomeini]] after the 1979 [[Iran hostage crisis]], which aired 14 days after the hostages were captured.<ref>{{cite web|title=1970s: Talking back to the Ayatollah Khomeini|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/media/mike-wallace-a-year-since-we-lost-him/6/|website=CBS News|accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref> Another famous story he produced was on the [[1990 Temple Mount riots]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lando|first1=Barry|title=Remembering Mike Wallace, A Jew Unafraid of the Truth|url=http://forward.com/news/154667/remembering-mike-wallace-a-jew-unafraid-of-the-tru/|accessdate=9 July 2015|work=Forward|date=April 12, 2012}}</ref> Wallace said of Lando and another producer, \"if it wasn't for [Marion Goldin] and Barry there would be no ''60 Minutes''.\"<ref name=mikewallace>{{cite book|last1=Rader|first1=Peter|title=Mike Wallace: A Life|date=2012|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=9781466802254|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OwOYQFjw-KgC|accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nLando pioneered the use of hidden cameras for investigative television reporting.<ref name=mikewallace /> He was awarded a [[George Polk award]] for Television Reporting in 1977.<ref>{{cite web|title=1977 George Polk Award Winners|url=http://www.liu.edu/Polk/Articles/Past-Winners#1977|website=Long Island University|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref> Lando and Wallace won a Robert F. Kennedy Journalism award in 1990 for the segment \"40,000 a Day.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carmody|first1=John|title=The TV Column|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1990/04/11/the-tv-column/b32dfe49-4fa1-429b-8ab7-fb066c6c1c81/|accessdate=8 July 2015|work=Washington Post|date=April 11, 1990}}</ref> Lando also won two [[Emmy]]s at ''60 Minutes''.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|title=Barry Lando|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/barry-lando/|website=Huffington Post|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Lando collaborated with Michel Despratx to produce a documentary for [[Canal+]] called \"Saddam Hussein, the Trial the World Will Never See.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Saddam's fair trial documentary|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2004/10/25/saddam%E2%80%99s-fair-trial-documentary|accessdate=9 July 2015|work=SBS|date=October 25, 2004}}</ref> Lando's 2007 book, ''Web of Deceit: The History of Western Complicity in Iraq, From Churchill to Kennedy to George W. Bush'', covered 85 years of Western intervention in [[Iraq]].<ref>{{cite news|title=WEB OF DECEIT by Barry Lando|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/barry-m-lando/web-of-deceit/|accessdate=8 July 2015|work=Kirkus Reviews|date=November 15, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Barry Lando on 'The History of Western Complicity in Iraq, From Churchill to Kennedy to George W. Bush'|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2007/1/30/barry_lando_on_the_history_of|accessdate=8 July 2015|work=Democracy Now!|date=January 30, 2007}}</ref> Lando has written for ''The Atlantic'', the ''Los Angeles Times'', the ''Christian Science Monitor'', the ''International Herald Tribune'', and ''Le Monde''.<ref name=bio />\n\n== ''Herbert v. Lando'' ==\n\nColonel [[Anthony Herbert (lieutenant colonel)|Anthony Herbert]] sued Lando and Wallace for libel for a 1973 ''60 Minutes'' broadcast that painted Herbert as a liar.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lubasch|first1=Arnold H.|title=COURT THROWS OUT LIBEL SUIT FILED AGAINST CBS BY COLONEL|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/01/16/nyregion/court-throws-out-libel-suit-filed-against-cbs-by-colonel.html|accessdate=8 July 2015|work=New York Times|date=January 16, 1986}}</ref> The case reached the [[United States Supreme Court]] as ''Herbert v. Lando'' 441 U.S. 153 (1979).<ref>{{cite web|title=HERBERT v. LANDO|url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-supreme-court/441/153.html|website=FindLaw|publisher=Thomson Reuters|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first=Brian E. |last=Gray |title=Herbert v. Lando: State of Mind Discovery and the New York Times v. Sullivan Libel Balance |volume=66 |journal=Cal. L. Rev. |issue=5 |year=1978 |accessdate=July 8, 2015 |url=http://scholarship.law.berkeley.edu/californialawreview/vol66/iss5/8 }}</ref> It was part of a series of appellate cases that set the boundaries of the press's right to publish information about private and public figures and an important authority for plaintiffs in defamation cases.<ref>{{cite web|title=Herbert v. Lando - Significance|url=http://law.jrank.org/pages/23091/Herbert-v-Lando-Significance.html|website=Law Library - American Law and Legal Information|publisher=Net Industries|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Herbert v. Lando - Impact|url=http://law.jrank.org/pages/23096/Herbert-v-Lando-Impact.html|website=Law Library - American Law and Legal Information|publisher=Net Industries|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n<!--- After listing your sources please cite them using inline citations and place them after the information they cite. Please see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. --->\n*\n*\n*\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last1=Coffey|first1=Frank|title=60 Minutes: 25 Years of Television's Finest Hour|date=1993|publisher=General Publishing Group|isbn=9781881649045|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/60minutes25years00coff}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Einstein|first1=Daniel|title=Special Edition: A Guide to Network Television Documentary Series and Special News Reports, 1980-1989|date=1997|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=9780810832206}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Rader|first1=Peter|title=Mike Wallace: A Life|date=2012|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=9781466802254|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OwOYQFjw-KgC}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite news|last1=Lando|first1=Barry|title=My Quarter Century With Mike Wallace|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/barry-lando/mike-wallace-dies-60-minutes_b_1412516.html|accessdate=9 July 2015|work=Huffington Post|date=June 9, 2012}}\n* [http://www.alternet.org/story/49864/how_george_h.w._bush_helped_saddam_hussein_prevent_an_iraqi_uprising Excerpt from ''Web of Deceit'']\n* [http://barrymlando.com/us-saddam-hussein-trial-of-saddam-hussein/ The Trial of Saddam Hussein]. 1994 documentary for [[Canal+]]. \n* {{cite interview |last=Lando |first=Barry |subject-link= |interviewer=[[Leonard Lopate]] |title=The West in Iraq |url=http://www.wnyc.org/story/53916-the-west-in-iraq/ |publisher=[[WNYC]] |date=July 2, 2007 |work=The Leonard Lopate Show |access-date=July 14, 2015}}\n* [http://barrymlando.com/ Personal website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lando, Barry}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Barry Lando\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1939|06|8|df=y}}\n| nationality        = Canadian\n| occupation         = Journalist, Author and Producer\n| television         = CBS' 60 Minutes\n| website            = http://BarryMLando.com/\n}}\n\n'''Barry Lando''' (born June 8, 1939) is a Canadian award-winning journalist, author, and former producer for [[CBS]]' ''[[60 Minutes]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Keefe|first1=Derrick|title=Web of Deceit By Barry M. Lando|url=https://www.straight.com/article-68130/web-of-deceit-by-barry-m-lando|accessdate=8 July 2015|work=Georgia Straight|date=January 31, 2007|location=Vancouver}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nLando graduated from [[Harvard University]] in 1961<ref>{{cite news|title=Students to Start New Publication|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1962/3/10/students-to-start-new-publication-pa/|accessdate=15 July 2015|work=Harvard Crimson|date=March 10, 1962}}</ref> and [[Columbia University]].{{citation needed|date=July 2015}} He was a producer for ''[[60 Minutes]]'' for over 25 years, most of those producing stories for [[Mike Wallace]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lando|first1=Barry|title=My Quarter Century With Mike Wallace|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/barry-lando/mike-wallace-dies-60-minutes_b_1412516.html|accessdate=9 July 2015|work=Huffington Post|date=June 9, 2012}}</ref> Lando produced the first interview with the [[Ayatollah]] [[Khomeini]] after the 1979 [[Iran hostage crisis]], which aired 14 days after the hostages were captured.<ref>{{cite web|title=1970s: Talking back to the Ayatollah Khomeini|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/media/mike-wallace-a-year-since-we-lost-him/6/|website=CBS News|accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref> Another famous story he produced was on the [[1990 Temple Mount riots]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lando|first1=Barry|title=Remembering Mike Wallace, A Jew Unafraid of the Truth|url=http://forward.com/news/154667/remembering-mike-wallace-a-jew-unafraid-of-the-tru/|accessdate=9 July 2015|work=Forward|date=April 12, 2012}}</ref> Wallace said of Lando and another producer, \"if it wasn't for [Marion Goldin] and Barry there would be no ''60 Minutes''.\"<ref name=mikewallace>{{cite book|last1=Rader|first1=Peter|title=Mike Wallace: A Life|date=2012|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=9781466802254|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OwOYQFjw-KgC|accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nLando pioneered the use of hidden cameras for investigative television reporting.<ref name=mikewallace /> He was awarded a [[George Polk award]] for Television Reporting in 1977.<ref>{{cite web|title=1977 George Polk Award Winners|url=http://www.liu.edu/Polk/Articles/Past-Winners#1977|website=Long Island University|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref> Lando and Wallace won a Robert F. Kennedy Journalism award in 1990 for the segment \"40,000 a Day.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carmody|first1=John|title=The TV Column|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1990/04/11/the-tv-column/b32dfe49-4fa1-429b-8ab7-fb066c6c1c81/|accessdate=8 July 2015|work=Washington Post|date=April 11, 1990}}</ref> Lando also won two [[Emmy]]s at ''60 Minutes''.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|title=Barry Lando|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/barry-lando/|website=Huffington Post|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Lando collaborated with Michel Despratx to produce a documentary for [[Canal+]] called \"Saddam Hussein, the Trial the World Will Never See.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Saddam's fair trial documentary|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2004/10/25/saddam%E2%80%99s-fair-trial-documentary|accessdate=9 July 2015|work=SBS|date=October 25, 2004}}</ref> Lando's 2007 book, ''Web of Deceit: The History of Western Complicity in Iraq, From Churchill to Kennedy to George W. Bush'', covered 85 years of Western intervention in [[Iraq]].<ref>{{cite news|title=WEB OF DECEIT by Barry Lando|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/barry-m-lando/web-of-deceit/|accessdate=8 July 2015|work=Kirkus Reviews|date=November 15, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Barry Lando on 'The History of Western Complicity in Iraq, From Churchill to Kennedy to George W. Bush'|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2007/1/30/barry_lando_on_the_history_of|accessdate=8 July 2015|work=Democracy Now!|date=January 30, 2007}}</ref> Lando has written for ''The Atlantic'', the ''Los Angeles Times'', the ''Christian Science Monitor'', the ''International Herald Tribune'', and ''Le Monde''.<ref name=bio />\n\n== ''Herbert v. Lando'' ==\n\nColonel [[Anthony Herbert (lieutenant colonel)|Anthony Herbert]] sued Lando and Wallace for libel for a 1973 ''60 Minutes'' broadcast that painted Herbert as a liar.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lubasch|first1=Arnold H.|title=COURT THROWS OUT LIBEL SUIT FILED AGAINST CBS BY COLONEL|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/01/16/nyregion/court-throws-out-libel-suit-filed-against-cbs-by-colonel.html|accessdate=8 July 2015|work=New York Times|date=January 16, 1986}}</ref> The case reached the [[United States Supreme Court]] as ''Herbert v. Lando'' 441 U.S. 153 (1979).<ref>{{cite web|title=HERBERT v. LANDO|url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-supreme-court/441/153.html|website=FindLaw|publisher=Thomson Reuters|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first=Brian E. |last=Gray |title=Herbert v. Lando: State of Mind Discovery and the New York Times v. Sullivan Libel Balance |volume=66 |journal=Cal. L. Rev. |issue=5 |year=1978 |accessdate=July 8, 2015 |url=http://scholarship.law.berkeley.edu/californialawreview/vol66/iss5/8 }}</ref> It was part of a series of appellate cases that set the boundaries of the press's right to publish information about private and public figures and an important authority for plaintiffs in defamation cases.<ref>{{cite web|title=Herbert v. Lando - Significance|url=http://law.jrank.org/pages/23091/Herbert-v-Lando-Significance.html|website=Law Library - American Law and Legal Information|publisher=Net Industries|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Herbert v. Lando - Impact|url=http://law.jrank.org/pages/23096/Herbert-v-Lando-Impact.html|website=Law Library - American Law and Legal Information|publisher=Net Industries|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n<!--- After listing your sources please cite them using inline citations and place them after the information they cite. Please see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. --->\n*\n*\n*\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last1=Coffey|first1=Frank|title=60 Minutes: 25 Years of Television's Finest Hour|date=1993|publisher=General Publishing Group|isbn=9781881649045|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/60minutes25years00coff}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Einstein|first1=Daniel|title=Special Edition: A Guide to Network Television Documentary Series and Special News Reports, 1980-1989|date=1997|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=9780810832206}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Rader|first1=Peter|title=Mike Wallace: A Life|date=2012|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=9781466802254|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OwOYQFjw-KgC}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite news|last1=Lando|first1=Barry|title=My Quarter Century With Mike Wallace|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/barry-lando/mike-wallace-dies-60-minutes_b_1412516.html|accessdate=9 July 2015|work=Huffington Post|date=June 9, 2012}}\n* [http://www.alternet.org/story/49864/how_george_h.w._bush_helped_saddam_hussein_prevent_an_iraqi_uprising Excerpt from ''Web of Deceit'']\n* [http://barrymlando.com/us-saddam-hussein-trial-of-saddam-hussein/ The Trial of Saddam Hussein]. 1994 documentary for [[Canal+]]. \n* {{cite interview |last=Lando |first=Barry 